{"title_page": "Parashorea lucida", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n|image =\n|status = CR\n|status_system = IUCN2.3\n|status_ref = <ref name=IUCN/>\n|genus = Parashorea\n|species = lucida\n|authority = ([[Friedrich Anton Wilhelm Miquel|Miq.]]) [[Wilhelm Sulpiz Kurz|Kurz]]<ref name=Ashton/>\n|synonyms = \n*''Parashorea stellata'' {{Au|[[Dirk Fok van Slooten|Slooten]] 1927, non Kurz 1870}}\n*''Shorea lucida'' {{Au|Miq.}}\n*''Shorea subpeltata'' {{Au|Miq.}}\n}}\n\n'''''Parashorea lucida''''' (also called '''white meranti''') is a species of plant in the family [[Dipterocarpaceae]]. The name ''lucida'' is derived from [[Latin]] (''lucidus'' = clear) and refers to the [[Leaf#Venation (arrangement of the veins)|venation]] on the leaf. It is a tall [[Rainforest#Emergent layer|emergent]] tree, up to 60 m tall, found in mixed [[dipterocarp]] forest on clay and clay soils. It is found in [[Sumatra]] and [[Borneo]].<ref name=Ashton/> It is threatened by [[habitat loss]].<ref name=IUCN/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist | refs =\n\n<ref name=IUCN>Ashton, P. 1998.  [https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/33098/all ''Parashorea lucida''].   [http://www.iucnredlist.org 2006 IUCN Red List of Threatened Species. ]  Downloaded on 23 August 2007.</ref>\n\n<ref name=Ashton>{{Cite book | last1 = Ashton | first1 = P. S. |date=September 2004 | contribution = ''Parashorea lucida'' (Miq.) Kurz | contribution-url = http://www.chm.frim.gov.my/backup/TFSS.vol4_5_6.pdf | editor1-last = Soepadmo | editor1-first = E. | editor2-last = Saw | editor2-first = L. G. | editor3-last = Chung | editor3-first = R. C. K. | title = Tree Flora of Sabah and Sarawak | volume = 5 | pages = 186 | publisher = [[Forest Research Institute Malaysia]] | isbn = 983-2181-59-3 | url = http://www.chm.frim.gov.my/Resources/Publications/Books/Floras/Tree-Flora-of-Sabah-and-Sarawak.aspx | version = (free online from the publisher, lesser resolution scan PDF versions) | accessdate = 11 November 2007 }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3016593}}\n\n[[Category:Parashorea|lucida]]\n[[Category:Critically endangered plants]]\n[[Category:Trees of Sumatra]]\n[[Category:Trees of Borneo]]\n[[Category:Flora of Sarawak]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Dipterocarpaceae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n|image =\n|status = CR\n|status_system = IUCN2.3\n|status_ref = <ref name=IUCN/>\n|genus = Parashorea\n|species = lucida\n|authority = ([[Friedrich Anton Wilhelm Miquel|Miq.]]) [[Wilhelm Sulpiz Kurz|Kurz]]<ref name=Ashton/>\n|synonyms = \n*''Parashorea stellata'' {{Au|[[Dirk Fok van Slooten|Slooten]] 1927, non Kurz 1870}}\n*''Shorea lucida'' {{Au|Miq.}}\n*''Shorea subpeltata'' {{Au|Miq.}}\n}}\n\n'''''Parashorea lucida''''' (also called '''white meranti''') is a species of plant in the family [[Dipterocarpaceae]]. The name ''lucida'' is derived from [[Latin]] (''lucidus'' = clear) and refers to the [[Leaf#Venation (arrangement of the veins)|venation]] on the leaf. It is a tall [[Rainforest#Emergent layer|emergent]] tree, up to 60 m tall, found in mixed [[dipterocarp]] forest on clay and clay soils. It is found in [[Sumatra]] and [[Borneo]].<ref name=Ashton/> It is threatened by [[habitat loss]].<ref name=IUCN/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist | refs =\n\n<ref name=IUCN>Ashton, P. 1998.  [http://www.iucnredlist.org/search/details.php/33098/all ''Parashorea lucida''].   [http://www.iucnredlist.org 2006 IUCN Red List of Threatened Species. ]  Downloaded on 23 August 2007.</ref>\n\n<ref name=Ashton>{{Cite book | last1 = Ashton | first1 = P. S. |date=September 2004 | contribution = ''Parashorea lucida'' (Miq.) Kurz | contribution-url = http://www.chm.frim.gov.my/backup/TFSS.vol4_5_6.pdf | editor1-last = Soepadmo | editor1-first = E. | editor2-last = Saw | editor2-first = L. G. | editor3-last = Chung | editor3-first = R. C. K. | title = Tree Flora of Sabah and Sarawak | volume = 5 | pages = 186 | publisher = [[Forest Research Institute Malaysia]] | isbn = 983-2181-59-3 | url = http://www.chm.frim.gov.my/Resources/Publications/Books/Floras/Tree-Flora-of-Sabah-and-Sarawak.aspx | version = (free online from the publisher, lesser resolution scan PDF versions) | accessdate = 11 November 2007 }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3016593}}\n\n[[Category:Parashorea|lucida]]\n[[Category:Critically endangered plants]]\n[[Category:Trees of Sumatra]]\n[[Category:Trees of Borneo]]\n[[Category:Flora of Sarawak]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Dipterocarpaceae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parashorea_lucida"}
{"title_page": "The Real Slim Shady", "text_new": "{{short description|2000 single by Eminem}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = The Real Slim Shady\n| cover      = Eminem - The Real Slim Shady CD cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Eminem]]\n| album      = [[The Marshall Mathers LP]]\n| released   = April 18, 2000\n| format     = [[CD single|CD]]\n| recorded   = 2000\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Comedy hip hop]]|[[hardcore hip hop]]}}\n| length     = {{duration|m=4|s=44}}\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Aftermath Entertainment|Aftermath]]|[[Shady Records|Shady]]|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Eminem|Marshall Mathers]]|[[Dr. Dre|Andre Young]]|[[Tommy Coster]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Dr. Dre]]|[[Melvin \"Mel-Man\" Bradford|Mel-Man]]}}\n| prev_title = [[Forgot About Dre]]\n| prev_year  = 2000\n| next_title = [[The Way I Am (Eminem song)|The Way I Am]]\n| next_year  = 2000\n| misc       = \n{{External music video|{{YouTube|FA2j9qlFyDU|\"The Real Slim Shady (Official - Dirty Version)\"}}}}\n{{Audio sample\n | type        = single\n | file        = Eminem - The Real Slim Shady.ogg\n | description = \"The Real Slim Shady\"\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''The Real Slim Shady'''\" is a song by American rapper [[Eminem]] from his third album ''[[The Marshall Mathers LP]]'' (2000). It was released as the [[lead single]] a week before the album's release. The song was later released in 2005 on Eminem's [[greatest hits]] album ''[[Curtain Call: The Hits]]''.\n\n\"The Real Slim Shady\" was Eminem's first song to reach number one in the [[United Kingdom]] and it also peaked at number four on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], giving him his biggest hit up to that point.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.songfacts.com/detail.php?id=1210|title=The Real Slim Shady}}</ref> The song was the 14th best selling of 2000 in the United Kingdom. It won multiple awards, including [[MTV Video Music Awards]] for [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Video of the Year|Best Video]] and [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Male Video|Best Male Video]], as well as a [[Grammy Award]] for [[Best Rap Solo Performance]].  In October 2011, ''[[NME]]'' placed it at number 80 on its list \"150 Best Tracks of the Past 15 Years\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/list/150-best-tracks-of-the-past-15-years/248648/page/8|title=150 Best Tracks Of The Past 15 Years|work=NME.COM|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref> It was listed at number 396 on ''NME''{{'}}s 500 greatest songs of all time.\n\n==Premise==\n{{original research|section|date=June 2015}}\n\"The Real Slim Shady\" was not originally intended to be part of ''[[The Marshall Mathers LP]]''. [[Interscope Records]]'s [[Jimmy Iovine]] wanted Eminem to have a song to introduce the album, similar to the way \"[[My Name Is]]\" was the first single on ''[[The Slim Shady LP]].'' Eminem, [[Dr. Dre]], [[Tommy Coster]] and [[Mike Elizondo]] wrote \"The Real Slim Shady\" just hours before the final copy of the album was due. The first single was intended to be \"Who Knew.\"<ref>''[[VH1]]'s Ultimate Albums: The Marshall Mathers LP''</ref>\n\nThe song is a critique of [[manufactured pop]] songs that were popular at the time. It was a hit single, becoming Eminem's first chart topper in some countries, and garnering much attention for insulting various celebrities, including:\n* Actress [[Pamela Anderson]]'s alleged abuse at the hands of her ex-husband, rocker [[Tommy Lee]] (''Jaws all on the floor, like Pam, like Tommy just burst in the door, and started whooping her *** worse than before, they first were divorced, throwing her over furniture'')\n* Eminem claims in one line to have murdered [[Dr. Dre]], and that he's locked him in his basement. This was a spin on one of his previous songs, \"[[My Name Is]]\", where Eminem says, \"And Dr. Dre said...\" then Dre comes on and says, \"Slim Shady, you're a basehead.\" (''And Dr. Dre said\u2014nothing, you idiots/Dr. Dre's dead, he's locked in my basement.'')\n* Comedian [[Tom Green]]'s [[bestiality|humping]] of a deceased [[moose]] on TV, and his song \"[[Lonely Swedish (The Bum Bum Song)|Lonely Swedish]]\". (''Sometimes, I wanna get on TV and just let loose, but can't/but it's cool for Tom Green to **** a dead moose.'')\n* Rapper [[Will Smith]]'s brand of commercialized and clean rap music and his [[MTV Video Music Awards|VMA]] acceptance speech where he boasted that he didn't need to curse or **** anybody on his records (''Will Smith don't gotta cuss in his raps to sell records/well, I do. So **** him, and **** you too.'') Eminem first dissed Smith in the music video in [[Dr. Dre]]'s \"[[Forgot About Dre]]\" when a news reporter asked him questions about the fire he and Dre started and he responded, \"Well I was just upstairs listening to my Will Smith CD\" in replacement to the middle of Eminem's verse due to the explicit lyrics.\n* Eminem mentions [[Britney Spears]] (''You think I give a **** about a Grammy?/Half of you critics can't even stomach me, let alone stand me/\"But Slim, what if you win, wouldn't it be weird?\"/Why? So you guys could just lie to get me here?/So you can sit me here, next to Britney Spears?'')\n* [[Christina Aguilera]] was angered by his claim that she performed [[oral sex]] on [[Fred Durst]] of the band [[Limp Bizkit]] and on [[Carson Daly]], an [[MTV]] [[VJ (media personality)|VJ]]. (''***, Christina Aguilera, better switch me chairs/so I can sit next to Carson Daly and Fred Durst/and hear 'em argue over who she [[fellatio|gave head]] to first.'')<ref name=\"people\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20278448,00.html |title=Eminem and His Many Feuds |magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=May 12, 2009 |last=Helling |first=Steve |accessdate=December 31, 2010}}</ref>\n* He also makes fun of the boy band [[NSYNC]] when he appears to dance in the video with the \"group\". (''I'm sick of you, little girl and boy groups, all you do is annoy me/so I have been sent here to destroy you.''). However, [[Chris Kirkpatrick]] was unhappy with this, so he called Eminem a \"bully\",<ref>https://www.dailydot.com/unclick/bridesmaid-toast-eminem-slim-shady/</ref> and Eminem attacked him with the song \"[[Without Me (Eminem song)|Without Me]]\".<ref>https://idobi.com/news/eminem-explains-his-disses-of-moby-chris-kirkpatrick-in-without-me/</ref>\n* He references the [[Bloodhound Gang]]'s song \"[[The Bad Touch]]\" (''They\u2019ve got the [[Discovery Channel]], don\u2019t they/We ain\u2019t nothing but mammals).\n\nThe chorus is about the sudden fashion changes caused by Eminem's success: \"I'm Slim Shady, yes I'm the real Shady/All you other Slim Shadys are just imitating/So won't The Real Slim Shady please stand up, please stand up, please stand up?\" The chorus imitates the [[catchphrase]] of the quiz show ''[[To Tell the Truth]]:'' \"Will the real ______ please stand up?\" In an interview <ref>{{Citation|last=Sirya ayriS|title=EMINEM speak about Curtain  Call  album 2005 on mtv Italy.|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TYQjEPVgOf4|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref> while promoting his greatest hits album, ''Curtain Call,'' Eminem remarked that the sound of the chorus was intended to recreate that of a chainsaw going off. The sudden jump and increase in tempo as well as pitch recreates the motor of a chainsaw coming to life.\n\n==Critical reception==\nPopMatters described this song: \"In a number of songs on the new album, including the current single, 'The Real Slim Shady,' Eminem slams his 'enemies' with comic book intensity. In the video, he wears a superhero costume and an insane asylum straitjacket while rapping, 'I'm sick of you little girl and boy groups, all you do is annoy me / So I have been sent here to destroy you / And there's a million of us just like me / Who cuss like me; who just don't give a **** like me / Who dress like me; walk, talk and act like me / And just might be the next best thing, but not quite me!' Of course, the irony is built into the song: Eminem's signature style the bleached blond hair, pale skin, humungous T-shirt has spawned droves of lookalikes and wannabes. Voila, he's a teen idol. Poor Em, can't win for losing.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/music/reviews/e/eminem-marshall.shtml|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060422004338/http://www.popmatters.com/music/reviews/e/eminem-marshall.shtml|title=Eminem: The Marshall Mathers LP - PopMatters Music Review|archivedate=22 April 2006|publisher=|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref> Allmusic highlighted the single.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-marshall-mathers-lp-mw0000062949|title=The Marshall Mathers LP - Eminem - Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards - AllMusic|author=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|work=AllMusic|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref> Will Hermes was positive: \"In the aftermath of Slim Shady, he married the girlfriend he imagined killing, while his mother, immortalized in his hit single 'My Name Is' (''I just found out my Mom does more dope than I do''), sued him for $10 million for defamation of character.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,276305,00.html | work=Entertainment Weekly | title=News Review: The Marshall Mathers LP | date=June 2, 2000}}</ref>  The defamation case was settled in 2001 for $25,000, with Debbie Mathers' former attorney being awarded $23,354\u2014netting Ms. Mathers just over $1600 for her efforts.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1444814/judge-decides-against-eminems-mother-in-defamation-suit/ | work=MTV News | title=Judge Decides Against Eminem\u2019s Mother In Defamation Suit | date=2001-06-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1446458/eminems-mom-nets-measly-1600-from-lawsuits-against-her-son/ | work=MTV News | title=Eminem\u2019s Mom Nets Measly $1,600 From Lawsuits Against Her Son | date=2001-08-08}}</ref> LA Times wrote: \"'The Real Slim Shady,' the first single from the album, is a modest step to the mainstream\u2014a fresh and funny, almost PG-rated swipe at everything from the Grammy Awards to shallow teen pop.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/2000/may/20/entertainment/ca-31967 | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Robert | last=Hilburn | title=Eminem's Latest Seems Sure to Delight Fans, Anger Parents | date=May 20, 2000}}</ref>\n\nIGN cited: \"The album's obligatory 'pop' number is exposed on 'The Real Slim Shady,' which chugs and lurches along to a boinging electro funk beat. It would be a total pop smash if it weren't for the lyrics, though. Leave it to Em to juice it up with ear candy effervescent, but keep the words in the subversive. As with the other Dre crafted tunes on the album, there's plenty of cool special effects bustling about\u2014fart noises, heavy breathing, all of it coalescing with Em's cartoon character on crystal meth delivery. Sure it's pop, but of the most demented nature.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2004/11/12/the-marshall-mathers-lp?page=2|title=The Marshall Mathers LP|work=IGN|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref> Rolling Stone praised the sound of the single: \"slick, bright, melodic funk that's so R&B-ish, you can dance to it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/the-marshall-mathers-lp-20000706|title=Eminem The Marshall Mathers LP Album Review|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref> It has been in many movies, including ''[[21 Jump Street (film)|21 Jump Street]]''. It has been one of his most well-known songs.\n\n==Music video==\nThe [[music video]] features Eminem performing the song in a psychiatric ward, a local Detroit neighborhood nearside a park, a fast-food joint, the Grammy Awards, and even in a factory where multiple clones of the rapper are produced. The video also features cameo appearances by [[Dr. Dre]], [[D12]], [[Fred Durst]], [[Kathy Griffin]], a lookalike of [[Kid Rock]], a lookalike of [[Carson Daly]], lookalikes of [[Pamela Anderson]] and [[Tommy Lee]], and even a stuffed [[Bill the Cat]] doll can also be seen being held in possession by one of the mental patients in the hospital scenes.\n\nActress and comedian [[Kathy Griffin]], who is also known for insulting celebrities in her act,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfist.com/archives/2006/07/24/kathy_griffin_dishing_and_swishing.php|title=Kathy Griffin: Dishing and Swishing|work=SFist|accessdate=25 April 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061104192430/http://www.sfist.com/archives/2006/07/24/kathy_griffin_dishing_and_swishing.php|archivedate=4 November 2006}}</ref> appears in the video as an attending nurse in a psychiatric ward. Griffin said during a July 21, 2005, interview on ''[[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno]]'' that Eminem selected her for the video because fellow rapper [[Snoop Dogg]] told him she was \"really funny.\"<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZjDUQ1sY--o|title=YouTube|publisher=|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe video also features Eminem dressed in the same superhero costume used by [[Tom Green]] in the \"[[Lonely Swedish]]\" video chasing [[*NSYNC]] lookalikes, taking [[Justin Timberlake]] down to the ground and putting 'his bum on the man's lips.'<ref>[http://www.mtv.com/news/1424805/nsync-aguilera-weigh-in-on-eminem-track/ Nsync Weigh In on Eminem Track]</ref> The costume can be seen later in the \"[[Without Me (Eminem song)|Without Me]]\" music video following the release of ''[[The Eminem Show]]''.\n\nThe video features scenes corresponding to specific lyrics:\n\n*Pamela Anderson and Tommy Lee chase each other around a couch and Anderson screaming in front of the camera. (''Like Pam, like Tommy just burst in the door, and started whooping her *** worse than before, they first were divorced, throwing her over furniture.'')\n*An obese man in underwear being enslaved by a [[dominatrix]] with a paddle. (''Yeah, I probably got a couple of screws up in my head loose, but no worse than what's going on in your parents' bedrooms.'')\n*Two young boys watch the [[Discovery Channel]] on television with two [[rhinoceros]]es mating, then looking at each other in awe, referring to the 1999 song \"[[The Bad Touch]]\", by [[Bloodhound Gang]]. (''Of course, they're gonna know what intercourse is by the time they hit fourth grade/They got the Discovery Channel, don't they?/\"We ain't nothing but mammals..\" Well, some of us cannibals'')\n*A [[gay marriage]] is shown and Eminem breaks up the two men about to kiss each other and showing disgust. (''But if we can **** dead animals and antelopes/then there's no reason that a man and another man can't elope'')\n*after saying the verse 1 Eminem performs in a private room with all his clones with platinum blonde hair, rapper jeans and white T-shirt produced from the factory with their arms crossed their heads bobbing to the music standing still in an underground subway on the face of the imitator of him. (the chorus: 'Cause I'm Slim Shady, Yes, I'm The Real Shady/All You Others Slim Shadys Are Just Imitating/So Won't The Real Slim Shady Please Stand Up?/Please Stand Up?/Please Stand Up?)\n**Within this screenshot you can see Eminem rapping in a pink coloured room full of men who look like the artist I believe that this is effective as it creates a clear image of the artist which will leave a lasting impression on the audience and make the artist recognisable to the audience.This is effective as this makes the location of this scene look like they are in an underground subway by the lights and the different pictures which are located around the walls and on the ceiling which creates a messy image for the artist.\n*It could also be a reference to how he got lost in the huge sea of his fans; at that time, he was popular so much, that teenagers dressed like him (white T-shirts and blue jeans) and dyed their hair blonde. The reference could be noticed in the video of this song where his fans with blonde hair and white T-shirts were standing behind him.\n*Eminem at the Grammy Awards dressed as [[Britney Spears]], along with [[Fred Durst]] and [[Carson Daly]] pulling a blow-up doll of Christina Aguilera between their seats towards each other angrily until it flies out of the chair. (''Christina Aguilera better switch me chairs so I can sit next to Carson Daly and Fred Durst, ang hear 'em argue over who she gave head to first.'')\n*In a factory you see white men transformed into Eminem clones, with platinum blonde hair, rapper jeans and white T-shirt.( And There's A Million Of Us Just Like Me Who Cuss Like Me, Who Just Don't Give A **** Like Me Who Dress Like Me, Walk, Talk And Act Like Me And Just Might Be The Next Best Thing, But Not Quite Me) \n*In the video for the song, a factory can be seen turning young white men into clones of Eminem, with hair dyed platinum blonde, baggy jeans and a plain white T-shirt.\n*A clip from a cartoon of a frog tap-dancing on a turtle (from the ''[[Flip the Frog]]'' film ''[[Fiddlesticks (film)|Fiddlesticks]]'') can be seen on a TV in the hospital and the viewer laughs at it.\n*Eminem works in a fictional fast-food restaurant with an 'Ask Me' patch giving a woman her order and rejecting it because of the onion rings being forgotten, however he gets the onion rings and he spits in them as a form of revenge for her rude treatment of him, and gives the onion rings to the woman to complete her order, which she begins eating as she walks away. The same scene also shows Eminem driving recklessly around in circles in a parking lot in a blue [[AMC Pacer]]. (''He could be working at Burger King, spitting on your onion rings/or in the parking lot, circling, screaming: \"I don't give a ****!\"/With his windows down and his system up'')\n*after saying the verse 3 Eminem performs in a private room with all his clones with platinum blonde hair, rapper jeans and white T-shirt produced from the factory with their arms crossed their heads bobbing to the music standing still in an underground subway watching the exit. (the chorus: 'Cause I'm Slim Shady, Yes, I'm The Real Shady/All You Others Slim Shadys Are Just Imitating/So Won't The Real Slim Shady Please Stand Up?/Please Stand Up?/Please Stand Up?)\n\nIn the uncensored version of the music video, the fat man in underwear wears a [[gag (BDSM)#Ball|ball gag]]; in the censored version, he does not. The edited version also does not show Eminem raises his middle fingers; instead, he points at the camera.\n\n==Credits==\nInformation from the interior booklet of The Marshall Mathers LP\n\nSinging And Lyrics : [[Eminem]]\nProduction : Dr. Dre And Mel-Man\nMixing : Dr. Dre\nBass, Guitar \u2013 Mike Elizondo\nKeyboards \u2013 [[Tommy Coster Jr.]]\nDirectors : [[Philip G. Atwell]] [[Dr. Dre]]\nApparences in the clip : [[Dr. Dre]] [[D12]] [[Fred Durst]] [[Kathy Griffin]] [[Kid Rock]] [[Carson Daly]] [[Pamela Anderson]] [[Tommy Lee]] [[Christina Aguilera]]\n[[NSYNC]]\n\n==Covers and parodies==\nParody songs include:\n* In the UK Queen-musical ''[[We Will Rock You (musical)|We Will Rock You]]'' the phrase ''Who (the Hell) is the real Slim Shady'' appears during an interrogation.\n*\"The Real Church Lady\", a ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' parody in \"Church Chat\" with [[Dana Carvey]]\n*\"The Real Greg Brady\", a song written and performed by [[Barry Williams (actor)|Barry Williams]].\n*\"The Real Rahim Jaffer\", a ''[[This Hour Has 22 Minutes]]'' parody performed by [[Rick Mercer]] and [[Cathy Jones]] in 2001 following the incident where one of Canadian Federal MP [[Rahim Jaffer]]'s aides posed as Jaffer in a radio interview.<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VXzJCL0_xmM|title=Will the Real Rahim Jaffer Please Stand Up?|date=23 April 2010|work=YouTube|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref>\n*\"The Real Sin Savior\", by Christian parody band [[Apologetix]]\n*\"The Real Sugar Baby\", by [[Stephanie Beard]].\n*\"Will the Real Slim Shady Please Shut Up\", a parody written and performed by a female rapper Emily Ellis, who is frequently confused with [[Christina Aguilera]]<ref name=people /><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,85411,00.html | work=Entertainment Weekly | first=Lori | last=Reese | title='Shady' Lady | date=August 2, 2000}}</ref>\n* A performance in the UK satirical [[mockumentary|spoof documentary]] ''[[Brass Eye]]'' in the controversial 2001 \"Paedogeddon\" episode. It features satirist [[Chris Morris (satirist)|Christopher Morris]] performing as a rapper, \"JLb-8\".\n* In their song \"On Passing Lilac Urine\" from the 2001 EP, ''Editor's Recommendation'', [[Half Man Half Biscuit]] sing \"I'm Slim Shady/I'm the real Slim Shady/the other Slim Shady's gone to play tennis\"\n*\"Will the Real Mitt Romney Please Stand Up?\", a viral video satire of [[Mitt Romney]], [[2012 United States presidential election|2012]]'s [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidate for [[President of the United States]], his [[Mitt Romney presidential campaign, 2012|campaign]], persona, [[Public image of Mitt Romney#Religion|religious beliefs]], gaffes, controversies and public-relations (PR) problems. The \"rap\" featured in this video is constructed almost entirely out of clips of Romney from a wide variety of public speaking engagements and interviews; a number of other politicians, including [[Barack Obama]], fill in the rest.\n*\"I'm not Omnistrife\"/\"Nem vagyok Omnistrife\", a parody song written and performed by the hungarian Fekete D\u00e1niel posing as [[Naruto]] character [[Hoshigaki Kisame]] in an animated video\n\nCover versions:\n*The song was featured in [[\"Weird Al\" Yankovic]]'s song \"Angry White Boy Polka\" on his album ''[[Poodle Hat]]''.\n*[[William Shatner]] performed a spoken word cover of the song during the \"[[Where No Fan Has Gone Before]]\" episode of ''[[Futurama]]'' prompting Melllvar to exclaim, \"He ''found'' a way.\" This is a parody of Shatner's spoken word music album ''[[The Transformed Man]]'', as well as his recitation of [[Elton John]]'s \"[[Rocket Man (song)|Rocket Man]]\" at the 1978 [[Saturn Awards]].\n*In an episode of ''[[Coronation Street]]'', [[Kirk Sutherland]] recited the main chorus of the song in order to win the heart of [[Fiz Brown]].\n*\"The Real Pacers Fans\", by [[Indianapolis, Indiana]]-based radio station RadioNow 93.1, when the [[Indiana Pacers]] were playing the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] in the [[2000 NBA Finals]].\n*In the final episode of [[Peter Kay's Phoenix Nights]], this was performed by Jerry St Clair ([[Dave Spikey]]) impersonating Eminem as part of the [[Stars In Their Eyes]] sequence.\n*\"Seurasaari Rap\" featuring [[Seurasaari]] Open Air Museum, [[Helsinki]], by Tapio Nurminen. The Finnish-language rap from 2000 deals with the museum, guides, their parties and the tourists.<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p2Il8JVQut8|title=Seurasaari Rap|date=19 August 2009|work=YouTube|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref>\n*ProjectRNL, an Israeli band did a progressive rock cover to this song.<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VBc2wv3eF1s|title=Slim Shady - The Musical|date=12 November 2010|work=YouTube|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref>\n*The song's instrumental was used in ''The \"Drink Wontons\" song'' (He hundun, \u559d\u6df7\u6c8c), a rap song sung in the [[Nanjing dialect]]. It became very popular with teenage [[Nanjing]]ers in 2006 and remains a great example of the so-called Nanjing dialect.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.synotrip.com/nanjing/tips-and-other-stuff/introduction-to-nanjinghua-528.shtml|title=Introduction to Nanjinghua|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=3 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n{{see also|List of awards and nominations received by Eminem}}\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Eminem Real Slim Shady VMAs.jpg|thumbnail|Eminem performing The Real Slim Shady at the 2000 VMAs.]] -->\n\"The Real Slim Shady\" was very successful at the [[2000 MTV Video Music Awards]], winning awards for [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Video of the Year|Video of the Year]] and [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Male Video|Best Male Video]], as well as being a nominee for [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Rap Video|Best Rap Video]], [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Direction|Best Direction]], [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Editing|Best Editing]] and [[MTV Video Music Award - Viewer's Choice|Viewer's Choice]]. The song was also performed by Eminem at the show with look-a-likes of himself, as in the video.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Organization\n! Award\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"10\" | 2000\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Billboard Music Award|''Billboard'' Music Awards]]\n| Maximum Vision Video\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Best Rap/Hip-Hop Clip of the Year\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[2000 Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Awards]]\n| Choice Music: Video\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| Choice Music: Summer Song\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" | [[2000 MTV Video Music Awards|MTV Video Music Awards]]\n| [[MTV Video Music Award for Video of the Year|Video of the Year]]\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Male Video|Best Male Video]]\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Rap Video|Best Rap Video]]\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Direction|Best Direction]]\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Editing|Best Editing]]\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| [[MTV Video Music Award for Viewer's Choice|Viewer's Choice Award]]\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2001\n| [[Detroit Music Awards]]\n| Outstanding National Single\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[43rd Annual Grammy Awards|Grammy Awards]]\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Solo Performance|Best Rap Solo Performance]]\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Track listing==\n;'''UK CD single'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Real-Slim-Shady-Eminem/dp/B00004VULM/ref=sr_1_1?s=music&ie=UTF8&qid=1332672587&sr=1-1|title=Real Slim Shady: Amazon.co.uk: Music|publisher=|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref>\n{{track_listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n\n| title1  = The Real Slim Shady\n| note1   =\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Eminem|Marshall Mathers]]|[[Dr. Dre|Andre Young]]|[[Tommy Coster]]|[[Mike Elizondo]]}}\n| extra1  = {{hlist|[[Dr. Dre]]|[[Melvin \"Mel-Man\" Bradford|Mel-Man]]}}\n| length1 = {{duration|m=4|s=44}}\n\n| title2  = The Real Slim Shady\n| note2   = instrumental\n| writer2 = {{hlist|Mathers|Young|Coster|Elizondo}}\n| extra2  = {{hlist|Dr. Dre|Mel-Man}}\n| length2 = {{duration|m=4|s=44}}\n\n| title3  = Guilty Conscience\n| note3   = radio version with new hook) (featuring [[Dr. Dre]]\n| writer3 = {{hlist|Mathers|Young}}\n| extra3  = {{hlist|Dr. Dre|[[Eminem]]{{small|{{ref|a|[a]}}}}}}\n| length3 = {{duration|m=3|s=19}}\n\n| title4  = The Real Slim Shady\n| note4   = video\n| writer4 =\n| extra4  =\n| length4 = {{duration|m=4|s=44}}\n\n| total_length = {{duration|m=|s=}}\n}}\n\n;'''UK Cassette'''\n{{track_listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n\n| title1  = The Real Slim Shady\n| note1   =\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Eminem|Marshall Mathers]]|[[Dr. Dre|Andre Young]]|[[Tommy Coster]]|[[Mike Elizondo]]}}\n| extra1  = {{hlist|[[Dr. Dre]]|[[Melvin \"Mel-Man\" Bradford|Mel-Man]]}}\n| length1 = {{duration|m=4|s=44}}\n\n| title2  = My Fault\n| note2   = pizza mix\n| writer2 = {{hlist|Mathers|[[Jeff Bass|Jeffrey Bass]]|[[Bass Brothers|Mark Bass]]}}\n| extra2  = {{hlist|[[Bass Brothers]]|[[Eminem]]}}\n| length2 = {{duration|m=3|s=53}}\n\n| total_length = {{duration|m=8|s=37}}\n}}\n\n;'''German CD single'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Real-Slim-Shady-Eminem/dp/B00005245H/ref=sr_1_11?s=music&ie=UTF8&qid=1332672587&sr=1-11|title=Real Slim Shady: Amazon.co.uk: Music|publisher=|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref>\n{{track_listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n\n| title1  = The Real Slim Shady\n| note1   =\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Eminem|Marshal